##In Wuhan, where the epidemic has spread, it is difficult for non-seriously ill patients to seek medical treatment

Health insight

Functional introduction, understand the health professional news

* Since the outbreak, Wuhan has requisitioned 50 hospitals as designated hospitals, and many of the non-new patients have either been cleared for treatment or have fallen ill during the outbreak and faced difficulties in seeking care.
* The-month-old girl, suffering from a rare congenital heart defect condition and in urgent need of surgery, was driven thousands of miles by her parents to "break through" the siege and sent to Beijing, but she had to wait 14 days at a quarantine point before being admitted to hospital.
* The 0-year-old leukemia patient, who suffered a relapse during chemotherapy and a new crown disease, could not be transferred to a better hospital and had to wait for a miracle.
* Two-year-old Wang Jianzhong, tuberculosis and kidney failure, after several twists and turns, in the coordination of the relevant departments, only to be admitted to hospital.
* Under the new crown epidemic, let the patient and the family to be troubled, is not only the medical resources are tight.

Since the outbreak of the new crown disease, Wuhan has requisitioned 50 hospitals as designated hospitals, and many non-new crown patients have either been cleared for treatment or have fallen ill during the epidemic and faced difficulties in accessing health care.

Eight-month-old Chen Jinyuan, who was suffering from a rare congenital heart defect disease and in urgent need of surgery, was driven thousands of miles by her parents to "break through" and take her to Beijing, but she had to wait 14 days at a quarantine point before being admitted to the hospital.

A 20-year-old leukemia patient, who suffered a relapse during chemotherapy and a new crown disease, could not be transferred to a better hospital and had to wait for a miracle.

Wang Jianzhong, 62, suffered from tuberculosis and kidney failure before being admitted to hospital under the coordination of the relevant authorities.

Under the severe new crown epidemic, lets the patient and the family to be troubled, also not only is the medical resources to be tight.

At a Beijing hotel chain in Xicheng District, Chen Hengyang and his eight-month-old daughter have been isolated for 10 days.

The 35-year-old Hubei Native drove 16 hours to Beijing 10 days ago to give his daughter life-saving heart surgery. But they can not immediately enter the already contacted hospital, according to policy, all people from Hubei into Beijing, must be concentrated isolation for 14 days, this is no one can cross the bottom line.

"To tell the truth, the child is so sick, and we are prepared for it ourselves, and this is the best way we can think of, " Chen Hengyang told eight o 'clock Jianwen. His daughter was supposed to be in Wuhan Union Hospital therapy, but because of the new crown, the surgery was postponed indefinitely.

Since the outbreak of the new crown disease in January, the Wuhan has responded to the growing number of confirmed cases by requisitioning a total of 50 hospitals in five waves to be designated as new crown pneumonia hospitals for the city. As of February 19,46 of them had been renovated and put into use, opening 19,989 beds.

Non-new patients who had previously been treated in these hospitals were cleaned up and discharged to facilitate the renovation. More serious patients can be isolated in the hospital, but can not proceed to the next treatment. Patients with rigid needs, the original hospital to help contact the replacement agencies, but not to ensure that 100% of the beds. More "temporarily controllable" patients can only return home, living in the "possible relapse" shadow.

On February 18, the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission released the list of hospitals for the medical treatment of special patients with non-new coronary pneumonia in the whole city, defining the corresponding hospitals according to six types, namely, acute cardio-cerebral vessels, trauma and other acute and critical diseases, hemodialysis, maternal and child, malignant tumors (including tumor of the hematopoietic and lymphoid tissues) and chronic diseases, facial diseases and burns. In addition to facial diseases and burns, the remaining 4 corresponding hospitals have more than 10.

As the number of dialysis machines in the hospital has increased, the situation of dialysis patients has basically improved, and most of the patients'regular needs can be met, a volunteer involved in dialysis patient services in Wuhan told eight o'clock Jianwen. "only a few patients suspected of infection need to go to a designated hospital in Niikappu for isolation and dialysis, but basic precautions are in place and there is no problem. "

Unfortunately, this document, which addresses the needs of most patients, does not help Chen at all. His daughter needs surgery as soon as possible to save her life, but with Wuhan's current medical resources, it is nearly impossible to perform surgery on a patient who is not a new crown.

At present, in Wuhan, and Chen Hengyang suffering from the same plight of the family is not a small number.

A rare female baby from Wuhan to Beijing for surgery

On the afternoon of Feb. 17, Chen posted a photo of his two young daughters on his microblog, writing: "after a week of isolation, Darling refuels. ". The photo was taken at a hotel chain near Dalian Road, Xicheng District, about 7 km from the Pediatric Surgery Center of Fuwai Hospital, the largest pediatric heart center in the world. If all goes well, his daughter will have surgery there in seven days.

"Our biggest concern right now is whether she will make it that far, and so far so good. "

Screenshot of △ Chen Hengyang's micro blog

On Feb. 10, to treat his daughter's illness, Chen drove his wife and daughter from Wuhan, Henan and Hebei, 1,200 kilometers, to Beijing the following afternoon.

On the same day, a family of three was arranged to stay in a designated isolation hotel in Xicheng District. In order to ensure the safety of his daughter during the 14-day isolation period, Chen Hengyang and his wife took care of her at all times. "The last thing she wants is to be deprived of oxygen, but we have no choice. This is her last chance. If it doesn't work out, we will be prepared. "

Chen Hengyang's daughter, Chen Jinyuan, was born in June 2019. On December 29, Xiao was taken to the Hubei Provincial Women's and children's Hospital for treatment of Fulminant Myocarditis and later transferred to the Wuhan Union Hospital for further treatment. On January 19, because of the impact of the new Crown Epidemic, the Union hospital advised Chen Hengyang discharge procedures, let her daughter at home rest. "We were afraid of getting infected ourselves, so we moved out. "

Since then, Xiaojinyuan's illness has gone through several iterations. In early February, at the risk of infection, Chen took his daughter to Concord Hospital for a CT angiography. The diagnosis was "anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery, " an extremely rare congenital condition, the incidence rate is only one in 300000 and the mortality rate is extremely high.

"The doctors at the hospital told me that they could take us to the hospital for Conservative treatment out of humanitarian reasons, but the operation would not work until the disease was better, " Chen said, according to an online search, it found that the disease had a mortality rate of more than 90 percent before the age of one, and the daughter was eight months old

Away from Her, Chen Hengyang learned from the group of patients, Beijing Fuwai Hospital in this area is very experienced, the success rate of surgery is very high, they decided to send their daughter to Beijing. He contacted Fuwai Hospital, the other side's response is, as long as they can get to Beijing, they accept, but must be isolated for 14 days. "The family talked about it and decided to do it anyway. Otherwise, if we wait another two months, we might not even have a chance to do it. "

By then, Wuhan had been closed to traffic for more than 10 days. Chen went to the community and brought his daughter's medical records. The community was reflected to the street, and the street was reflected to the district. Finally, the District Epidemic Prevention Headquarters issued him a special pass. The only requirement is to drive yourself. Fortunately for Chen Hengyang, it only took him two days from the time he submitted his materials to the time he got the pass certificate.

February 10 at 10:00 pm, with his daughter in the Concord Hospital after a cardiac injection, Chen Hengyang and his wife started the car. He chose this time because he was afraid that there would be too many bayonets during the day, and in case he was deported, all his efforts would be wasted. Fortunately, the journey went smoothly, "after 16 hours of driving, it was almost nonstop. There were inspectors in every service area. They were afraid to go in, " Chen wrote on his Weibo Account. "They took turns asking questions and could cry with all kinds of explanations. "

For Chen Hengyang, the most intense interrogation took place at the exit of the Beijing Expressway, "I had to look at my id before I let them go because the kids were in the car and they knew I wasn't lying. But at the Beijing Expressway, he kept questioning me for half an hour, asking me what I was doing in Beijing, whether the hospital had contacted him, where he was staying, and then he had to report back to his superiors, but in the end he let us down."

Fortunately, the day after they left, Wuhan announced that it was closing all its residential areas around the city.

Today, Chen posts daily about his daughter's isolation in Beijing. From time to time, well-meaning people ask him if he needs help and suggest that he open a fund-raising channel. He replied that his trip out, the original controversy is quite big, many people think he is using his daughter's illness to escape Wuhan, this time to fund-raising will deepen the misunderstanding.

Leukemia girl in concord waiting for a miracle

Wan Ruyi, a 20-year-old girl from Wuhan, is less fortunate than Xiao Jinyuan, who is already in Beijing awaiting surgery. She doesn't even have the chance to take risks. Because no other hospital would take her, she stayed in the Wuhan Union Hospital Ward, waiting for a miracle.

Wanruyi is suffering from acute lymphocyte leukemia, which has undergone three rounds of chemotherapy since being diagnosed last May. The original treatment, through chemotherapy to temporarily control cancer cells, so that the body to bone marrow transplant conditions. But on November 5 last year, after the end of chemotherapy reexamination showed that the cancer cells in Wanruyi body recurrence, the first stage of treatment failed.

On 11 November, Wanruyi was readmitted to the hospital for Cart treatment over a period of 89 days, again with the aim of creating the conditions for a final transplant. Unfortunately, two and a half months later, the disease returned for the second time.

Wan Ruyi's mother, Wu Qiong, revealed that on January 29, her daughter began to suffer from leg pain. On January 31, she went to the hospital for a bone puncture. The results would have been known three days later, but because of the new crown disease, doctors were either transferred to the front line or were sent home to rest, the entire hematology department is practically paralyzed. "On February 8, the child was in so much pain that we contacted the hospital office, which called the professor, who checked the results himself and confirmed it was a relapse. "

Attending experts told Wu Qiong, based on the current situation, Concorde has been unable to recommend her daughter to a higher level of hospital, perhaps there is a chance. Wu Qiong says, this hope fire, was snuffed out very quickly. She tried to contact two of the country's best blood hospitals, one in Hebei, the other in Beijing, the other heard that she was Wuhan, immediately refused treatment.

To Wu's Chagrin, she contacted both hospitals in mid-january when CART was still in progress, hoping to get a bone marrow transplant later on, when both were willing. The hospital in Hebei even made bins for them. "It's a bit of a regret to think that there was no epidemic then, " he said. "If I had just taken the risk and turned around, maybe things would have been different. "

Wu Qiong said that the treatment for more than half a year, the daughter has been tortured exhausted physically and mentally. The side effects of vomiting, ulcers and diarrhea haven't gone away since chemotherapy last May. Hair and eyebrows have all fallen out. Once I looked in the mirror and cried about how I looked like an alien. Because the chemotherapy had hurt her spleen and stomach, she could only eat the stewed turnips and carrots for several months at a time. These are nothing, the most unbearable is the pain, the attack, the heart-rending cry, the face will be ferocious to change.

"She said to me, euthanasia, too tired, let us live their own life, forget her, a dog walk... you say we parents how can promise down. "

Lunch for all the people (photo by Wu Qiong)

In order to save her daughter as much as possible, Wu Qiong gritted her teeth and decided to have two more rounds of chemotherapy, which was the only way she could think of. "All I can think about is keeping her here for as long as I can. Both hospitals have said they will send us as soon as the outbreak is over. "

But she was unsure what the "end of the epidemic" would be and how long it would take.

WHO's struggling to find a doctor

"Why is it that these diseases that can normally be taken care of by ordinary hospitals can now kill people? " In recent days, Wang Xin has made more than a hundred phone calls for the sole purpose of keeping his father, Wang Jianzhong, alive through dialysis in Wuhan.

Wang Jianzhong, 62, was diagnosed with tuberculosis in October 2019 and has been on medication since then. On February 14 this year, he was diagnosed with acute renal failure due to the side effects of the drug. His Serum Creatinine was as high as 1,450 MOL / L (50-100 Mol / L as normal) , in medicine, this means severe damage to the kidneys and a near loss of detoxification. At that time, Wang Jianzhong had appeared breathing difficulty, Purple Lips, dysuria, because can not lie in bed, even have to sit at night to sleep.

Wang Xin, who had married in Hunan, contacted his family's community for the first time, hoping they would arrange a hospital for his father. Because Wang Jianzhong also had typical symptoms of pneumonia, the community reported a suspected case of the new crown. Early in the morning of February 17, the Taikang Tongji Hospital, which had been transformed and taken over by military doctors, called and said it could be treated.

Wang Xin was hesitant at first, because Tongji University was the designated hospital for patients with NCP, and his father didn't actually have NCP, he just needed dialysis. "I told them that my father was not a suspected case and that we could have an isolation ward. Later there came another person to the phone, the tone is very stern, asked my father whether or not suspected, if not, crossed out our names. If it is, they come and enforce it."

The attitude of the staff is related to the epidemic prevention policy. Two days ago, Wang Hesheng, a member of the Standing Committee of the provincial Party Committee who "parachuted" into Hubei Province, said at a press conference of the State New Administration of the People's Republic of China at his first public appearance that he wanted to ensure that all confirmed and suspected patients were admitted, this has become the short-term Hubei Epidemic Prevention and control of the first priority.

Wang Xin told the truth, and her father was disbarred, perhaps the most regrettable decision of her life. That day, Wang Jianzhong's illness suddenly aggravated, began to urinate blood, go to the toilet when kneeling directly in front of the toilet.

The couple took community taxis to three hospitals in the district, including Wuhan's Tongji Hospital, the fifth people's Hospital and the Hanyang Hospital, all of which were inaccessible. In Tongji Hospital, Wang Jianzhong's wife, who is in her 60s, knelt down for the doctor on the spot. The answer was still no.

On the other hand, Wang Xin called the first, second, ninth, Puren and Puai hospitals in Wuhan, according to a list provided by the community, and all were turned down. There are two reasons: first, Wang has the underlying disease of tuberculosis, which can spread to other patients, and second, the hospital's dialysis machines are running at full capacity, unable to take in new patients.

A volunteer suggested that she try to find a hospital in Hunan that would accept her father, then apply for a special pass to get him out of Wuhan. But the road did not go through, Wang Xin contacted a number of hospitals in Hunan, the other side said, must be after 14 days of isolation before admission, this is the bottom line.

"Now we just need command to coordinate and find a hospital to put my father on dialysis, even in the new crown designated hospital, even if he is infected with the virus, it doesn't matter, let's keep him here! "

At least things are finally turning around. On the evening of February 19, Wang Xin told eight o'clock that her father, coordinated by local authorities, had been admitted to a Hanyang Hospital for dialysis.

By xiaoqiong Mao
